segments.text: Each of us works so much alone as we travel around the state and work intensively with one student as chair that sometimes the five of us don't interact a whole lot together enough to keep our feet out of our mouths, hopefully.
Although we've had a time or two of that, too.
And you have the smallest group in the whole college, right?
We've asked for a sixth job line for the next budget year.
Sure, with that amount of graduates here, that's hard.
Was there anything else in the way of an insider?
observation, an anecdote, anything that stands out that happened that might be of interest that would not be in any of the documents.
It's just strictly a personal thing comes to mind.
OK. On the culture of the college, and this is not a question that I've been asking.
It just came about through this paper.
The beliefs, the feelings, the values, the perceptions of people.
What did you feel about the culture?
And I guess you can't have one for the whole college because every single floor or every single department is so different.
You would have a department culture, or in our case, you'd have an adult ed culture and an ed tech culture.
And once in a while, the loops will overlap.
But there is a big balloon that is the College of Education in terms of belief systems.

When Karian came and he was first pushing the idea of inquiry groups and wanted to, he said he wanted to do away with departmental lines and have different kinds of alliances, which makes a lot of sense.
And everybody sort of, because he was so different from Hubert, everybody sort of stood and looked at him for about a year and said, uh-huh.
And then sort of tried to make the inquiry thing work.
And it ran out of steam.
What do you think?
Was it just a lack of time, lack of enthusiasm?
What combination?
Or leadership?
Because I know a lot of people have talked about it, and there's a lot of written material on the inquiry groups.
but none on why it's fizzling or has fizzled.
That's a difficult thing to look at.
For one thing, the annual inquiry days have been continued whether there was a need for them or not.
And so orders have gone forth saying, thou shalt attend if you are intact.
The first year, or the first couple of years, everybody went with the kind of excitement, or at least most people went with a sort of excitement.
And I don't know.
I think, in all honesty, sometimes it seems that the dean is perhaps preoccupied or very busy with other things and not really paying attention to what's happening at home.
At home?
at in the college.
In the college, OK. And I realize that he is pulled in a lot of ways with national and international responsibilities.
And so that.
But sometimes it seems like nobody's riding their horse.
OK, that was that into the decision making part.
Is there a feeling then that vagueness as to who is making the decisions or riding the horse, as you put it very well?
If it wasn't for Brian Cole, I'm not sure that many, well, I will go ahead and say that I'm not sure that many things would be done.
I think he's riding the horse.
A lot.

Now, I do not know, I'm not privy to the degree to which he'd carve and see eye to eye on a lot of things, because I don't go to the policy committee except when Don's out of town and things of that nature.
But I think, from my perception, there seems to be somewhat of a vacuum in the leadership at the top.
And I have to also say, because I've been on the tenure advisory committee for the college and I'm chair this year, that I have watched Currigan agonize over the decisions.
We're not an extra layer of approval.
We are there to advise and assist the dean in making his recommendations.
Are you talking about the tenure?
Tenure and promotion.
Your chairman, what is the committee name again?
Tenure and Promotion Advisory Committee, TAPC.
Several years ago, I guess it was about four or five years ago, the Faculty Advisory Committee of the college, by lots of discussions and so forth, decided that there ought to be this group
And the idea was taken to the policy committee, and they approved it.
And the first year, Jerry Capus and Ernie Getz and I were elected.
You have to be tenured and so forth.
And we drew straws.
And I lost and got the three-year straw.
But we rotate so that whoever's on for the third year, the third year of their term, they're automatically chaired.
So that I'm chair this year, Hurley's chair next year, McNamara's chair the year after that, and we elect one each year.
And no two from any one department.
That's just for the tenure and promotion?
Tenure and promotion.
And what we do is read all the stuff that the departments send forward to the dean, and then try to think of any
relevant, pertinent, or impertinent question which we ought to raise with the dean regarding the information, but we do not have any vote or any say.
Nor should we.
It's not our role.
So the ultimate say is the dean's?
The ultimate say is the dean's.
And I've watched him agonize over these things, and I have become, though I'm not often impressed by department heads just categorically,
I am impressed with the care and concern they give to the letters they write recommending or not recommending somebody's position.
Most of them have a department committee, and that recommendation comes forward, and then the department head's recommendation comes forward.
And the dean looks at it.

as he said over and over, and I've now watched him two years, and I really think he means this, that he looks at these things from the perspective of, if this person was not a faculty member of the college, how would we miss what that person contributes?
From that perspective, he makes his recommendation, and sometimes it agrees with the departments, and sometimes it doesn't.
If that person was not here, in what ways would we miss him or her?
From the college level.
Right.
He expects the department to look at it from the discipline level, both locally and nationally.
And they know that.
And does that criteria work pretty well?
It seems to.
It seems to.
Then it goes forward to the provost's office, and they look at it from still a different perspective.
Which, do you know what that is?
I would say funding, research, teaching, service.
But then that's my bias again.
I think although the words they use aren't that.
Everybody was nervous as a cat when McDonald became provost.
An engineer?
A non-pupil person.
We don't know yet what he's like.
And the communication, what has that changed, the communication between?

The communication comes in an annual memo from Kent Phillips, known as the Phillips Memo, which sets forth the procedures that will be followed for the recommendations for tenure and promotion that year.
And they vary a little each year.
Now, does every department have very, very specific delineated
criteria, because I have only seen one.
And I haven't been asking, but one particular department shared it with me.
And it was, I mean, pages and pages of everything that has to be done.
There is a notebook that you can see.
It's in every office.
This is what we did the first year of the TAPC.
We visited with each faculty.
We found out what the procedures were.
If there were not procedures, we yelled and screamed until procedures were written.
We compiled a book of them for the college.
gave each office, each department office, a copy of the book and a brief summary of the thing to each faculty member.
We called meetings of the assistant professors for them to talk about what they're worried about.
Had the dean there.
We called a meeting with the associate professors, but it got canceled.
So I don't know when we're going to do that again.
But we've been working to try to be sure that people understand the basis on which they will be judged.
That's general for the college.
Does every department in itself have a separate one?
That's what's in that notebook.
Oh, and are they pretty uniform among departments?
Are they very different?
Because they need to be.
The departments are different.
The disciplines are different.
So that is something that you got input from each department?
A faculty of five is different from a faculty of 51.
Yes, every department has it.
No.
Okay, so there is a book that I can get all of them together.
Yeah, if anybody gives you any hassle, come up.
I've got a copy of the whole thing.
But there should be one in every office, every apartment.
Very good.
And, of course, we already talked a little bit about, well, you said a little bit about what you wished or would like to see the future hold.
What realistically do you think might be happening in the College of Education?
I think inertia.
I only learned one thing in high school physics, and that's inertia.
A moving body tends to continue in the direction in which it's moving.
Oh, is that upward, hopefully?
No.
No?
The whole college isn't?
I don't know.
I see it more level enough.
I don't think it's down.
I think it's level.
Just grind on the way it's going.
Because the damn daily takes time and energy away from somebody jamming fist into the machinery and saying, look, let's look at this.
Although, I'm sure people are looking at what the legislation means to the college.
Well, it will impact the undergraduate a lot more than it would anyway.
So yours is probably not going to be as good.
Do you see the IDD department or what did you call it?
It's an administrative unit.
Unit becoming a department any time?
No.
The politics of higher ed in Texas is such that I don't believe it will ever be put forward as a department.
It really gives them a direct deal of flexibility if it isn't.
The trouble is,
Some of the dean's staff, when I have gone to policy committee, they will talk about the five departments, and they'll have five copies of stuff.
And number six is sitting there saying, can we see a copy of that?
One of them especially does that rather consistently, and it's not Brian Cohen.
That's interesting.
We think so, too.
So there's a message there of one kind or another.
Now, where does this adult ed and all the things that are in IDED in College of Education at A&M, where do they fit in in other colleges?
What are they a part of, or how are they?
Some of them are in departments of administration.
That's for administration of education.
That's where it was at BU where I took mine.
Some are in adult and continuing education.
It varies.
There are about 50 adult ed programs in North America.
Where does the A&M program fit in?
In that 50, do you have any?
Pretty high.
In spite of the fact that we don't have any national scholarships and therefore have trouble recruiting nationally, we do most of our recruiting in the state of Texas.
But we've had a number of students, well, one guy from Canada, some from other countries, who come and say, well, you know, I want in this program because I think it's the best.
Of course, we think it's the best.
Have you... Do you have to do a lot of...
aggressive recruiting, or are the students not coming to you in great numbers?
Our students are our best recruiters.
We're going to shoot some of them if they keep dragging in students.
We've had to put a limit here in San Antonio.
Is that a problem?
It's the size of class.
That's a good problem, I guess.
It's not true in Corpus or El Paso, but we have a viable group in each place.
How did the loss of two of your
five faculty members at one time affect the continuity or the flow of the department?
Were you able to, were the new people able to?
We had to cancel only one class.
But we covered all the rest.
The hardest part has been inheriting chairs of committee.
Because Ken and Adrienne are coming on fast, but it takes a while to catch on to all the bureaucratic Mickey Mouse that goes with this job.
So this December, five people who my chair will graduate.
Two were mine, two were Gary's, one was Bob's.
You can't say no.
It gets a little hairy.
Before I turn off the tape, we continue.
Is there anything that you'd like to summarize or end with?
In spite of the fact that my first year on this faculty was the hardest year of my employed career for lots of complicated reasons, I really liked working here.
It turned out to be the best job I ever had.
And if I could have found a way to quit that first year, I would have.
But I couldn't because of family commitments here.
But I'm glad I couldn't.
Never mind.
Very good.
I thank you for sharing all these insights with me.
And if I have some additional questions, I hope that you let me come back.
Oh, sure.
